	<p class="section_head">
	Aliases vs. Attributes
	</p>
	<p>
	<a href="aliases.jsp">Aliases</a> are alternate names for people, places or things. <i>Lad</i> is identified as an alias of <i>Tom</i> 
	in the <i>Tom Sawyer</i> template, for example. (<i>Tom</i> is defined as the short name of <i>Thomas</i>, 
	though it could as easily have been defined as an alias).
	</p>
	<p>
	<a href="attributes.jsp">Attributes</a> are not names, but objects, or concepts, or descriptions that are unique to a person, place, or thing 
	and which should probably be changed if you redefine a profile. In the <i>Dracula</i> template, for example,
	<i>an English Bradshaw's Guide</i> is defined as an attribute of the location <i>England</i>. 
	<i>English Bradshaw's Guide</i> is a guide to tourist locations in the United Kingdom. If you change 
	the location England to, say, California in your <i>Dracula</i> project, you might want to remap the <i>Bradshaw's</i> 
	attribute to something associated with the American west&mdash;<i>Sunset Magazine</i>, perhaps, or <i>Fodor's Guide to California</i>. 
	</p>
	
